HEADWORD: Genital
<hw>Gen"i*tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>genitalis</ets>, fr. <ets>genere</ets>, <ets>gignere</ets>, to
beget: cf. F. <ets>g⟦eacute⟧nital</ets>. See <er>Gender</er>.]</ety>
<def>Pertaining to generation, or to the generative organs; <as>as,
<ex>genital</ex> herpes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Genital cord</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>a cord
developed in the fetus by the union of portions of the Wolffian and
M⟦uum⟧llerian ducts and giving rise to parts of the urogenital passages
in both sexes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

